          "body": "Verse 11 opens the chapter's second movement with the most concentrated Christological portrait in Scripture: heaven opened, white horse, *Faithful and True*, righteous judge, eyes of fire, many diadems, secret name, blood-dipped robe, *The Word of God*, sword from the mouth, iron rod, winepress treader, *KING OF KINGS, AND LORD OF LORDS*. Each detail layers meaning. The eyes of fire (1:14; 2:18) penetrate every concealment. The many diadems answer the dragon's seven (12:3) and the beast's ten (13:1) — He wears every crown the pretenders wore. The secret name (v. 12) declares that even at the moment of fullest revelation, the Son remains beyond creaturely exhaustion. The blood-dipped robe in Isaiah 63:1-6 is the blood of His trodden enemies; some commentators (Beale, Caird) hold it is His own atoning blood, since His robe is dipped *before* the battle. The strongest reading takes both: the One who shed His own blood to save now sheds the blood of His enemies in righteous judgment, and the same robe carries both meanings."
