          "body": "The chapter's most chilling literary device is the parallel between *the marriage supper of the Lamb* (v. 9) and *the great supper of God* (v. 17). Both are called *deipnon* — the main evening meal. At one supper the bride feasts with the Lamb; at the other, the birds gorge on the flesh of the armies who opposed Him. The angel standing in the sun (v. 17) summons the birds with the same vocabulary the angel of v. 9 used to call the saints. Ezekiel 39:17-20 is the explicit Old Testament background — Gog's defeat as a sacrificial feast for carrion birds. The chapter forces the reader to choose between the two suppers. Every human being will be at one of them; no one sits out. The same Christ presides over both."
